subsection.p:
Previously we noted that the derivative of f(x)=x^2 is f'(x)=2x. We derived this from our limit definition of the derivative. If we use the limit definition to find the derivative of g(x)=x^3 we have:

g'(x)= \mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to0}\frac{(x+h)^3-x^3}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{x^3+3x^2h+3xh^2+h^3-x^3}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{3x^2h+3xh^2+h^3}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0} 3x^2+3xh+h^2=3x^2

Thus, the derivative of g(x)=x^3 is g'(x)=3x^2.

 If we use the limit definition to find the derivative of h(x)=x^4 we have:

h'(x)=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to0}\frac{(x+h)^4-x^4}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{x^4+4x^3h+6x^2h^2+4xh^3+h^4-x^4}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4x^3h+6x^2h^2+4xh^3+h^4}{h}
=\mathstrut \amp \lim_{h\to 0} 4x^3+6x^2h+4xh^2+h^3=4x^3

Thus, the derivative of h(x)=x^4 is g'(x)=4x^3. We note a pattern here, where the power "comes down" and new power is one less then the old. We now generalize  this.

p.p:
         Use the rule for power functions to compute the derivatives of the following functions. 



f(x)=x^8 


h(x)=x^{4.2} 


g(x)=\sqrt{x}=x^{1/2}

         Using the rule for power functions,
         we can compute the following derivatives.



f'(x)=8x^7 


h'(x)=4.2x^{3.2} 


\displaystyle g'(x)=\frac{1}{2}x^{-1/2}=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}} 

         For part c we use the fact that the square root can be rewritten as a \displaystyle  \frac{1}{2} power.

         Use the rule for power functions to compute the derivatives of the following functions. 



\displaystyle g(z)=\frac{1}{z^3}=z^{-3} 


\displaystyle h(t)=t^{7/5} 


\displaystyle f(q)=q^{\pi}

         Using the rule for power functions,
         we can compute the following derivatives.



\displaystyle g'(z)=-3z^{-4} 


\displaystyle \frac{dh}{dt}=\frac{7}{5}t^{2/5} 


\displaystyle \frac{d}{dq}[q^{\pi}]=\pi q^{\pi-1}

